edgeR Results

SARTools.edgeR.Kallisto.Transcripts.byGroup/SARTools.edgeR.Kallisto.Transcripts.byGroup_report.html

Initial Summary

Both DESeq2 and edgeR produced similar results with DESeq2 providing slightly fewer DE transcripts (as usual). The results indicate that there are not major differences between most of the groups and that only a few transcripts are significantly DE.

DESeq2:

#Number of features down/up and total:
#Test vs Ref                  # down # up # total
#Combination vs Control       0      7    7      
#Cort vs Control              1      6    7      
#Pregnanedione vs Control     2      1    3      
#Cort vs Combination          1      0    1      
#Pregnanedione vs Combination 29     11   40     
#Pregnanedione vs Cort        26     21   47

edgeR:

#Number of features down/up and total:
#Test vs Ref                  # down # up # total
#Combination vs Control       0      3    3      
#Cort vs Control              0      2    2      
#Pregnanedione vs Control     0      0    0      
#Cort vs Combination          0      0    0      
#Pregnanedione vs Combination 14     3    17     
#Pregnanedione vs Cort        7      4    11

There is nothing in the Data Exploration that would indicate that there is a problem with the reads or the analysis. The distribution of transcript abundances are similar in all groups and the fitting of the data to the DESeq2 and edgeR models appears good.

The main issue appears to be that there is a confounding factor that has divided the samples into two groups. This can be clearly seen in either the heirarchical cluster (Figure 6) or the MDS/PCA plots (Figure 7) for both analyses.

edgeR MDS plot

One possible explanation is that the two groups represent male and female. I will try to confirm this using differential expression of transcripts between the groups.
